Commit Message: Initial commit.
Added a setuptools script.
Added a pylint configuration.
Added common utilities modules.
Added a version file.
Added data readers for parsing on-disk data representations, like YAML.
Moved IDX utilities into the utils package.
Added Logger classes.
Added Engine classes for template substitutions.
Added Source classes, which are responsible for actually handling an individual data stream.
Added Provider classes, which are responsible for aggregating and collating data from Source for the purpose of providing the training/evaluation system with nicely matched-up data.
Added Supplier classes, which are helper classes that produce one or more named Sources.
Added the Backend base classes.
Added Loss classes with a Categorical Crossentropy placeholder (no supported backends yet).
Added Optimizer classes, along with an Adam placeholder (no supported backends yet).
Added Container classes, which are the internal representation of the model specification.
Added some simple containers.
Added Model class (which assembles the tensor graph from the container representation) and the core train/evaluation functionality.
Added evaluation hooks (pipe-like operations that may have access to ground truth information).
Fixed import for IDX module.
Added Specification parsing class, which is a convenience class that makes parsing specification files very easy.
Added package init module.
Added command-line script.
Added Keras as a backend (requires h5py, keras, and theano/tensorflow).
Added Keras support to the placeholder loss function and optimizers.
Added a couple new backend-agnostic containers.
Added several new containers that are supported by Keras.
Added MNIST example.
Added CIFAR-10 example.
Added stub for unit tests.
Added "build" command to the Kur script.
Allow Dense layers to use a shorthand notation: a single integer for size, or a list of integers for multiple dense layers in a row.
Simplified the "expand" layer to accept a single integer.

Added an auto-flattening feature to Dense layers; they now (by default) insert Flatten layers immediately before the Dense layer. This may be changed in the future to make the Model automatically add a Flatten container instead.
The MNIST supplier now supplies 3D images; it basically adds in the dim=0 expansion in the supplier rather than in the model. Thus, all images are now 1 channel plus width * height.
Additional debug statements for the Provider.
Added support for top-level "include" sections in a specification file.
Simplified the MNIST example using an "include" section.
Initial layout for documentation.
Moved to separate documentation source and build directories.
Added EnvironmentalVariable context manager. Keras backend is now more careful about checking/setting the backend, and ensures that the dimension ordering is correct.
Auto-flattening is disabled by default. It didn't work as intended. Need to track this either in the model construction or in shapes. Probably both.
Validation/testing now shows the average loss in real-time. Training shows the average--rather than instantaneous--loss now, too.
Deep merge utility uses "blend" as the default merging strategy.
Added Keras as a dependency in order to have a default backend installed.
Made the CIFAR-10 example more complex, and added lots of comments to the specification.
Tweaked the MNIST example.
Built out a large section of documentation covering the introduction and examples.

Keras backend now fakes pre-compiling data using 1-vectors instead of 0-vectors. This makes it better for additions like CTC.

Model compiling in Keras backend does not protect the model from loss-function extensions. This is intentional, since retracting extensions that describe containers that need to be connected to data will cause the training process to fail, since the training process uses input/output names to resolving data sources. We will revisit this in the future to determine the long-term solution.

Changed the way that the "activation" arguments work for convolutional and recurrent layers. For convolutions, the "activation" argument is now longer supported, since it can be confusing (why have an activation in the convolution definition as well as a separate activation type?). For recurrent layers, we now have an "outer_activation" argument. Keras calls this an "activation," but it is different from the way "activation" is interpretted for convolutional layers. Instead, the default "outer_activation" for recurrent layers is now the ReLU.

Module debug (#91)

* Added a new parameter to
kurfile->backend:
  gpu_busy_load: (5.0 default)

sets the maximum load before a GPU is considered 'busy' and excluded.

* Minor change to allow plugins to correctly register parameters when kur is run by calling python -m kur instead of running as a consul script.
added missing merge functions for pytorch backend

pytorch_backend now allows multiple outputs from a layer to be returned. So, for example, an output shape from a layer can now be '((None, a), (b))'. Of course, a any loss function used must take this into account.

patch for python 3.7 StopIteration change
